# UniPilot Git Workflow

Version control and team participation are graded. Follow these rules for all commits.

## Team Participation (mandatory)
- The project must show GitHub commits authored by **all team members**.
- Each member must have a visible, meaningful contribution history — not a single bulk commit.
- Do not commit on behalf of another member; each member commits under their own GitHub identity.
- Before submission, verify the GitHub contributors graph shows every team member.

## Commit Message Format (conventional commits)
```
<type>: <description>

<optional body>
```
Types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `docs`, `test`, `chore`, `perf`, `ci`

- Write clear messages focused on the "why".
- Commit feature by feature; avoid giant mixed commits.

## Feature-by-Feature Delivery
- Implement one feature at a time — do not build the whole project in one go.
- For each feature, in order:
  1. Implement the feature (TDD: tests first).
  2. Add unit, integration, E2E, and relevant security/stress tests.
  3. Update `README.md` if run/test instructions changed.
  4. Commit with a conventional message.

## README Upkeep
- `README.md` must always explain how to run the app (Docker first-run command) and how to run the tests.
- Keep README instructions in sync with the actual commands after every change.

## Pre-Commit Safety
- Never commit secrets or `.env` files. Commit `.env.example` instead.
- Ensure the app still builds/runs in Docker and tests pass before pushing.
- Run the security checklist (no plaintext passwords, validation, rate limiting) before committing.

## Pull Requests
- Analyze the full commit history, not just the latest commit.
- Use `git diff <base-branch>...HEAD` to review all changes.
- Write a clear PR summary and a test plan.
- Push new branches with `-u`.
